@node "forew" "Foreword on PV 37.01"
@{title "VERSION 37.01 FOR VILLAGE V2.58 or V3.9"}

PV prevents memory header corruption crashes while APM owns the board by
fixing a bug of village library: that library doesn't check if the board
is in use and always initializes itself and takes over the board even if
the board is already in use by someone else.
In other words PV is a tool to add or remove patches from the village
library file.
After installing the PV patch, any program that needs to drive the board
directly can just lower the CONFIGME bit in the cd_Flags of product
2167/11 to be sure that village library will never initialize itself until
the bit is low.

@{title "WHY ALL THIS HAPPENS?"}

The village library once stored in sys:expansion can be loaded only by the
BindDrivers command which checks if the board configme bit is high before
loading any library. APM since its first release always cleared the
configme bit while using the memory not allowing BindDrivers to load the
library.@{par}
The new Picasso II+ installation script puts the village.library straight
in the libs: drawer, allowing the library to be loaded by everybody, and
since the library doesn't chech the configme bit on its own it always
takes control of the board even if it is not allowed to do so.

@{title "WHY I DID IT"}

I could fix the bug letting APM install a kludge to prevent exec from
opening the village library while APM was in use, but this is the bad way
to solve problems: adding kludges to the OS is not my lifestyle, and any
program that owns the board without using the village library has to add
the same kludge. Programmers know how hard can be to manage SetFunction()
without a patch manager installed...@{par}
The best way, as I said, is to let village library properly arbitrate
the board once for all: by this patch the library now checks the configme
bit before attempting to take control over the board.

@{title "KLAUS, HOW CAN I CONTACT YOU?"}

As far as I know, village.library is maintained by Klaus Burkert. Klaus,
I don't know how to reach you via E-Mail, so here is the hint. To put this
arbitration in the source code, look in the InitFunction of the library,
the point where product 11 is checked the first time there should be a "If
board address is zero, then abort initialization" statement, you may
change it in "If board address is zero or configme bit is high, then abort
initialization". Maybe you can add it also in products 12 and 13 ;-)

@endnode
@node "usage" "Using PV 37.01"
@{title "REQUIREMENTS"}

PV is a pure program that runs on any Amiga shell under kick 2.0 and later
releases with 4 Kb or more of stack memory.

@{title "WHEN AND WHERE"}

PV is a tool to add or remove patches from the village library file, it
does not add anything harmful in the case the patch is not mandatory.
Once installed the patch, you can always revove it.
It is recommended to always patch village library, but it is mandatory in
all setups that do not load the village library by the BindDrivers
command.

@{title "ARGUMENTS"}

FROM/A = this is the mandatory source file name
@{par}
TO = this is an optional destination file name, if omitted PV will
overwrite, if necessary, the source file.
@{par}
INSTALL/S = this switch tells PV to install the polite patch in the file
specified by from/a (village library from now on will check the configme
bit).
@{par}
REMOVE/S = this switch tells PV to remove the polite patch in the file
specified by from/a (village library from now on will ignore the configme
bit).

@{title "ADVANCED SWITCHES USAGE"}

If you don't specify any switch, PV will just inform you if the file
specified by from/a is a patched or not village library.
@{par}
If you specify both switched, PV will patch original files and will
remove the patch from patched files.
@{par}
If you specify the INSTALL/S switch, PV will patch the original files and
will not resave the patched files.
@{par}
If you specify the REMOVE/S switch, PV will remove patches from the
patched files and will not resave the original files.

@{title "RETURN CODES"}

OK (0) tells that everything went as expected, WARN (5) tells that the
file was not saved as source and destination contain the same data, ERROR
(10) tells that something was wrong in the command line syntax, FAIL (20)
tells that something went wrong reading or writing the file, or that the
file is not a supported village library version or not a village library
at all.

@endnode
@node "messa" "Messages of PV 37.01"

@{title "STATUS MESSAGES"}

These messages appear when the from/a file is found and loaded.

@{msg "LOADING xx AS LIBRARY Vnn.nn"}
file "xx" has been loaded and recognized as a supported library version.

@{msg "xx IS NOT A VALID VILLAGE.LIBRARY FILE"}
file "xx" has been loaded but not recognized as a supported library
version, a list of supported versions will follow this statement (actually
2.58 and 3.9).

@{title "ACTION MESSAGES"}

These messages appear after the status messages.

@{msg "FILE IS A ORIGINAL LIBRARY"}
the file is a village library that ignores the configme bit, it will not
be resaved.

@{msg "FILE IS A PATCHED LIBRARY"}
the file is a village library that checks the configme bit, it will not
be resaved.

@{msg "RESTORED ORIGINAL CODE"}
the file was a village library that checked the configme bit, it will now
be saved as one that ignores the configme bit.

@{msg "INSERTED NEW CODE"}
the file was a village library that ignored the configme bit, it will now
be saved as one that checks the configme bit.

@{title "OTHER MESSAGES"}

Standard localized error messages appear whenever a dos error occurs.

@endnode
@node "patch" "Details about the patches"

@{title "HOW IT WORKS"}

I added a bit test instruction in a fragment that checks if the memory
board found its place in the Zorro-II addresing space. I was lucky enough
to find enough room to insert my new code without expanding the library in
size.

@{code}
input:   A4=pointer to execbase
output:  A0=configdev address
scratch: D0-D1/A0-A1 (all other registers must be preserved)

  @{"  " link "init258old"} village.library 2.58: old initfunction
  @{"  " link "init258new"} village.library 2.58: new initfunction
  @{"  " link  "init39old"} village.library 3.9 : old initfunction
  @{"  " link  "init39new"} village.library 3.9 : new initfunction
@{body}

@endnode
@node "histo" "Releases list from 33.01 to 37.01"
@next "main"
@{title "DEVELOPMENT"}

I write and test PV on an A3000/030-25, 2 Mb chip, 8 Mb fast, 2 Mb
Picasso-II.@{par}
Before releasing each new version to the public I test the program under
enforcer and kick 40.70.

@{title "RELEASE HISTORY"}

@{rev "37.01 (20-Jun-96)"}
PoliteVillage first public release. Thanks to:@{par}
Paolo Maggi for reporting that village opened when APM was active

@endnode
@node "init258old" "village.library: initfunction - old 2.58"
@prev "patch"
@{code}
	INCDIR	"include:"
	INCLUDE	"exec/types.i"
	INCLUDE	"libraries/configvars.i"
	INCLUDE	"libraries/expansion_lib.i"
	IFND	NULL
NULL	EQU	0
	ENDC

** fragment of village.library v2.58 (27-apr-94) initfunction
**********************************************************************
** hunk offset: $55c - file offset: $57c (48 bytes)

oldcode	move.l	#2167,d0		; manufacturer: village tronic
	moveq	#11,d1			; product: picasso 2/2+ memory
	movea.l	#NULL,a0
	move.l	a6,-(a7)
	movea.l	a4,a6
	jsr	_LVOFindConfigDev(a6)
	movea.l	(a7)+,a6
	move.l	d0,($e4).l		; reloc32 of hunk0+$e4 at hunk0+$576
	tst.l	d0
	beq	oldcode+1396
	movea.l	d0,a0
	move.l	cd_BoardAddr(a0),d0
	tst.l	d0
	beq	oldcode+1396

	END
@{body}
@endnode
@node "init258new" "village.library: initfunction - new 2.58"
@{code}
	INCDIR	"include:"
	INCLUDE	"exec/types.i"
	INCLUDE	"libraries/configvars.i"
	INCLUDE	"libraries/expansion_lib.i"

** fragment of village.library v2.58 (27-apr-94) initfunction
**********************************************************************
** hunk offset: $55c - file offset: $57c (48 bytes)

newcode	move.l	#2167,d0		; manufacturer: village tronic
	moveq	#11,d1			; product: picasso 2/2+ memory
	suba.l	a0,a0
	exg.l	a4,a6
	jsr	_LVOFindConfigDev(a6)
	exg.l	a4,a6
	move.l	d0,($e4).l		; reloc32 of hunk0+$e4 at hunk0+$570
	beq	newcode+1396
	movea.l	d0,a0			  @{b}
	btst	#CDB_CONFIGME,cd_Flags(a0)
	beq	newcode+1396		  @{ub}
	tst.l	cd_BoardAddr(a0)
	beq	newcode+1396

	END
@{body}
@endnode
